{"cursor":"72940","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Interventions infobox\n | Name = EEG Image = EEG_cap.jpg Caption = An EEG recording at Dalhousie\n | University ICD10 = ICD9 = MeshID = D004569 OPS301 = OtherCodes =\n}} spike and wave discharges monitored with EEG]] 'Electroencephalography'\n('EEG') is the recording of electrical activity along the scalp. EEG measures\nvoltage fluctuations resulting from ionic current flows within the neurons of\nthe brain. In clinical contexts, EEG refers to\nthe recording of the brain's spontaneous electrical activity over a short period\nof time, usually 20â40 minutes, as recorded from multiple electrodes placed on\nthe scalp. Diagnostic applications generally focus on the spectral content of\nEEG, that is, the type of neural oscillations that can be observed in EEG\nsignals. In neurology, the main diagnostic application of EEG is in the case of\nepilepsy, as epileptic activity can create clear abnormalities on a standard EEG\nstudy. Atlas of EEG & Seizure Semiology. B. Abou-Khalil; Musilus, K.E.;\nElsevier, 2006. A secondary clinical use of EEG is in the diagnosis of\ncoma, encephalopathies, and brain death. A third clinical use of EEG is for\nstudies of sleep and sleep disorders where recordings are typically done for one\nfull night, sometimes more. EEG used to be a first-line method for the diagnosis\nof tumors, stroke and other focal brain disorders, but this use has\ndecreased with the advent of anatomical imaging techniques with high\n(","linknr":1396,"url":"Electroencephalography","recorded":1362508957,"links":87,"instances":["eeg","medicine","observational","physiologist","star_wars","neuroanatomy","electricity","medical","medicine"],"pdf":["http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=MImg&_imagekey=B6SYX-4FV4S6H-1-1&_cdi=4846&_user=10&_orig=browse&_coverDate=02%2F28%2F1998&_sk=998939997&view=c&wchp=dGLbVzz-zSkWb&md5=47fbbe7e51a806779716fba415b96ab7&ie=/sdarticle.pdf","http://www.sciencedirect.com